{{Infobox book 
| name         = Linguistic Atlas of Chinese Dialects
| author       = [[Cao Zhiyun]]
| language     = Chinese
| country      = China
| subject      = [[Dialect geography]]
| publisher    = Commercial Press
| title_orig   = Hànyǔ Fāngyán Dìtú Jí 汉语方言地图集
| orig_lang_code = zh
| release_date = 2008
| media_type   = Print
}}
The '''''Linguistic Atlas of Chinese Dialects''''' ({{zh|s=汉语方言地图集|p=Hànyǔ Fāngyán Dìtú Jí}}), edited by [[Cao Zhiyun]] and published in 2008 in three volumes, is a [[dialect atlas]] documenting the geography of [[varieties of Chinese]]. Unlike the ''[[Language Atlas of China]]'' (1987), which maps the distribution of both minority languages and Chinese dialect groups, the new atlas is a collection of [[map]]s of various features of dialects, in the tradition of the ''[[Atlas linguistique de la France]]'' and its successors.{{sfnp|Kurpaska|2010|p=57}}{{sfnp|Iwata|2010|pp=100–101}}

== Methods ==
[[File:Map of sinitic languages full-en.svg|thumb|upright=2|Top-level groups of Chinese varieties identified in the ''[[Language Atlas of China]]'', used in the selection of survey sites for the dialect atlas]]
The project spanned 8 years, from 2001 to 2007.
A year of preparatory work began in December 2001, including selecting survey sites, codifying fieldwork procedures and conducting trial surveys.{{sfnp|Cao|2008|p=2}}{{sfnp|Cao|Liu|2012|p=142}}

The 930 sites throughout China and Taiwan were selected so that there was usually one site per county in southeast China and one site in every three or four counties in the [[Mandarin Chinese|Mandarin]] and [[Jin Chinese|Jin]] areas, preferably in non-contiguous counties.{{sfnp|Cao|Liu|2012|pp=143–144}}
Thus, for example, there were 92 sites each in [[Guangdong]] and [[Hubei]], but only 19 in [[Sichuan]] and 21 in [[Shaanxi]].{{sfnp|Cao|2008|p=4}}
The metropolitan district of each of 36 cities – provincial capitals plus [[Suzhou]], [[Xiamen]] and [[Meizhou]] – was included as a survey site.
The remaining 894 sites were generally chosen to be representative of rural dialects of their county, so dialect islands were omitted.{{sfnp|Cao|Liu|2012|p=144}}

A questionnaire was compiled, to elicit the pronunciation of 425 characters representing common Chinese morphemes, the local term for 470 items and the local form of 110 grammatical forms.{{sfnp|Cao|Liu|2012|p=145}}
Of the 930 sites selected, 91 sites were identified as key sites representing various dialect subgroups, to be subject to additional surveys.{{sfnp|Cao|Liu|2012|p=144}}
At these sites [[tone sandhi]] phenomena were to be investigated, and a much longer character list would be used.{{sfnp|Cao|Liu|2012|p=145}}

Fieldwork was conducted between December 2002 and December 2006, and the resulting data entered into a [[geographic information system]].{{sfnp|Cao|2008|p=2}}{{sfnp|Cao|Liu|2012|p=142}}
The 46 fieldworkers, 34 of whom held doctoral degrees in Chinese dialectology, were assigned to areas they were already familiar with.{{sfnp|Cao|Liu|2012|p=145}}
A single informant was used from each site, typically a male born between 1931 and 1945 who had spent almost all of his life at the site.{{sfnp|Cao|Liu|2012|p=144}}
This was in line with the usual practice in [[dialect geography]] elsewhere in the world of using nonmobile, older, rural males (NORMs), as such informants are considered more likely to reflect the traditional speech of the area.{{sfnp|Chambers|Trudgill|1998|pp=29–30}}

The maps were compiled and collated throughout 2007.{{sfnp|Cao|2008|p=3}}{{sfnp|Cao|Liu|2012|p=143}}

== Contents ==
The finished work consists of 510 maps, each containing data for all 930 sites, in three volumes:{{sfnp|Cao|2008|pp=6–7}}{{sfnp|Cao|Liu|2012|p=146}}
# ''Yǔyīn juǎn'' 语音卷 [Phonetics] (205 maps), {{ISBN|978-7-100-05774-5}}. These maps trace various significant [[phonetics|phonetic]] developments from earlier forms of Chinese, such as the development of the [[tone (linguistics)|tonal]] categories, [[voice (phonetics)|voice]]d initial [[obstruent]]s, initial consonants in [[palatal consonant|palatal]] environments and consonantal codas.{{sfnp|Cao|Liu|2012|pp=146–147}}
# ''Cíhuì juǎn'' 词汇卷 [Lexicon] (203 maps), {{ISBN|978-7-100-05784-4}}. Most of the [[lexicon]] maps show the particular expression used at each site for a given concept, displayed as [[Chinese characters]] standing for cognate morphemes.{{sfnp|Cao|Liu|2012|pp=147–148}}
# ''Yǔfǎ juǎn'' 语法卷, [Grammar] (102 maps), {{ISBN|978-7-100-05785-1}}. The [[grammar]] maps show the distribution of different syntactic constructions or grammatical morphemes.{{sfnp|Cao|Liu|2012|pp=148–149}}
In each map of the atlas, the different forms are classified, but the classifications are not explained, and must be deduced by the reader.{{sfnp|Iwata|2010|p=101}}
A digital version of the atlas is in preparation, to include additional maps and the full survey data.{{sfnp|Cao|Liu|2012|p=150}}

